SUMMARY:Everyone Wants A Village\, But No One Wants To Be A Villager
DESCRIPTION:Meaningful Dialogue 🗣️🔊\nI often hear phrases like: "I
 t takes a village to raise a child\\!" \\| "Everyone needs a community\\!"
  \\| "We need friends in life to combat loneliness\\!" but the truth is\\\
 , pretty much no one has the time or care for one and another\\. Leading t
 o feelings of loneliness and sadness whenever we try to make new friendshi
 ps only to be met with: "Sorry\\\, I'm just too busy right now\\." Well\\\
 , who the hell isn't busy?\\!\n\nI've often noticed the people who constan
 tly preach the importance of community & friendship\, but are unwilling to
  put in the effort of being a good friend.\n\nI understand that friendship
 s gets harder as we grow older due to different life trajectories ranging 
 from families to careers. However\, I still think we have a choice to be a
  good friend for others.\n\n**Humans are intrinsically social creatures an
 d we need each other. So how do we foster small communities in our world w
 hen almost no one is available?**\n\n**Questions to Ponder:**\n\n* Is the 
 American notion of individualism a detriment to the collective mental well
 being?\n* What is a good friend to you?\n* Are you too cynical about peopl
 e?\n* Why is it harder to have new friends as we grow older?\n* Can someon
 e with opposing politics and religious beliefs be your friend?\n* Is it be
 st practice to find people with common interests to become friends with?\n
 * Do you care about what other people are going through?\n* Are we obligat
 ed to care about other people?\n* When does self-care become narcissistic?
 \n* Are you more judgmental or empathetic?\n* Are people truly to busy to 
 care about others or are they using being busy as an excuse to avoid other
 s?\n* Why do some people give up on finding friends completely and live a 
 life of solitude?\n* From your experience\, do you find most people insuff
 erable?\n* Are most people fake?\n* Are all relationships and friendships 
 transactional?\n* Do you fear making new friends because you fear you migh
 t drag them down with your own negativity?\n* How do you feel when another
  person uses you to vent their feelings?\n* Are you looking for friends ju
 st to talk or get together and do things?\n* Should you tolerate an asymme
 try friendship?\n* Why do most friends stop texting you as soon as you don
 't keep reaching out? (Does it seem one sided?)\n* Do you see the best in 
 people?\n* Do you see the worst in people?\n* Is human nature more selfish
  or altruistic?\n* To what extent should tolerate negativity from friends?
 \n* What kind of things should we tolerate or no tolerate from friends?\n*
  What do you think is the worst that can happen when revealing vulnerabili
 ties to others?\n* Is showing vulnerability a sign of strength or weakness
 ?\n* Do most people have an ulterior motive in seeking friendships?\n* Was
  friendship more intimate back then?\n* Should we compromise our core valu
 es to gain friends?\n* What are somethings you're uncompromising about?\n*
  Do you value honest conflict or dishonest harmony?\n* Is technology like 
 social media making people more social or more lonely?\n* Do you fear that
  political polarization is making prospects of friendship more difficult?\
 n* How can we be better friends for others?\n\n**Guidelines**:\n\n* **If y
 our name on Zoom does not match your Zoom name\, you will be removed or no
 t admitted.**\n* Hand raises are required. There are no limits on how many
  times you can raise your hand.\n* There will be a 2-3 minute timer for ev
 ery person depending the size of attendees. However\, in this group\, I do
  allow a brief back and fourth interjection from others if it's something 
 that's related to the person who was just speaking. This is a way to preve
 nt the group from feeling too "robotic" in style and get your pressing que
 stion asked to the speaker and get the answer right away without waiting a
 ll the way back to your turn again.\n* Be authentic & civil!\n* Please ref
 rain from using Ad Hominem (personal) attacks. This includes in voice\, in
  meeting chat\, and in the comments section below. Instead\, please attack
  the points from others. Severe Ad Hominem such as racist behavior will re
 sult in being removed from the meeting.\n* Zoom link is posted well before
  the day of the meeting but you will not be able to join until 10 minutes 
 before the meeting start time.
